<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1085,2011]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,376,1085,1111]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Taxonomic history</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Warren, W." box="[392,576,1085,1111]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241" pagination="493 - 582" refId="ref14797" refString="Warren, W. (1904) New American Thyrididae, Uraniidae and Geometridae. Novitates Zoologicae, 11 (1), 493 - 582." type="journal article" year="1904">Warren’s (1904)</bibRefCitation>
description of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1904" box="[870,991,1085,1111]" class="Insecta" family="Thyrididae" genus="Loxiorhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[870,991,1085,1111]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Loxiorhiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
included 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pagenstecher" authorityYear="1892" box="[1106,1332,1085,1111]" class="Insecta" family="Thyrididae" genus="Siculodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cervinalis">
<emphasis box="[1106,1332,1085,1111]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Siculodes cervinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. He also noted that 
<taxonomicName authority="Pagenstecher, 1892" authorityName="Pagenstecher" authorityYear="1892" box="[269,619,1121,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Thyrididae" genus="Zeuzerodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[269,396,1121,1147]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Zeuzerodes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Pagenstecher, A." box="[403,619,1121,1147]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241" pagination="5 - 131" refId="ref14434" refString="Pagenstecher, A. (1892) Ueber die Familie der Siculiden (Siculidae) Guenee. Deutsche entomologische Zeitschrift. &quot; Iris &quot;, 5 (1), 5 - 131." type="journal article" year="1892">Pagenstecher, 1892</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is distinct from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1904" box="[803,924,1121,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Thyrididae" genus="Loxiorhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[803,924,1121,1147]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Loxiorhiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, justifying the description of the new genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="241" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1085,2011]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1157,1183]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1904" box="[331,452,1157,1183]" class="Insecta" family="Thyrididae" genus="Loxiorhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[331,452,1157,1183]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Loxiorhiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from the remaining genera of 
<taxonomicName box="[996,1111,1157,1183]" class="Insecta" family="Thyrididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Siculodini">Siculodini</taxonomicName>
by: (i) wings with an ocher ground color with irregular dark gray spots, more abundant on the ventral face (
<figureCitation box="[1051,1119,1193,1219]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–4" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1302,1326]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,842,1278]" captionTargetId="figure-231@8.[151,1436,842,1278]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 3–4. Loxiorhiza and Meskea species in dorsal (A and C) and ventral (B and D) views. 3. L. cervinalis, A–B: male from Bolivia, Santa Cruz, Buenavista (NHMUK 010921576); C–D: female from Brazil, Goiás, Leopoldo Bulhıes (NHMUK 010921560). 4. M. dyspteraria, A–B: male from USA, Texas, Hidalgo, Pharr (Bentsen-Rio Grande Valley State Park) (MGCL); C–D: female from El Salvador, San Salvador (ZSM). Scale bar 1cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4475217" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4475217/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); (ii) male with setae on the anal margin; (iii) saccus with setae; (iv) valva with editum; (v) fultura superior sclerotized with spines; (vi) vesica with cornuti; (vii) signum oval and (viii) papillae anales suboval.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="241" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1085,2011]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,1301,1327]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Redescription</emphasis>
. Forewing: length—males 18.6 mm (n = 13), females 18.6 mm (n = 11); male with slightly convex outer margin, female with anterior half slightly concave and posterior half straight, both sexes with diffuse dark gray line between R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[376,384,1391,1405]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">5</subScript>
–M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[423,431,1391,1405]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">3</subScript>
on both sides; retinaculum above Sc.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1085,2011]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">
Hindwing: length—males 10.9 mm (n = 13), females 11.3 mm (n = 11); both sexes triangular, nearly half the size of the forewing; dark gray diffused line on both sides between M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[942,950,1463,1477]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">1</subScript>
–M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[989,997,1463,1477]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">3</subScript>
; dorsal surface with darker distal half; male with a tuft of setae on anal margin close to the base; male with one and female with two bristles in the frenulum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1085,2011]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[380,451,1553,1579]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1338,1362]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,857,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-130@10.[151,1435,857,1314]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Male genitalia of Loxiorhiza cervinalis from Brazil, Mato Grosso do Sul, Miranda (Bodoquena mountain) (CEIOC 003). A) ventral view. B) lateral view. C) inner view of valva. D) dorsal view of tegumen and uncus. E) dorsal view of aedeagus. F) lateral view of aedeagus. Scale bar 1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4475223" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4475223/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
): tegumen rectangular in dorsal view, with rounded posterior angles, posterior margin with slight medial indentation; saccus suboval in lateral view, with numerous long and thin setae in the distal portion; uncus triangular, base with small lateral lobes and with posterior tip curved ventrally, thin and short setae immediately posterior the base; gnathos thin, U-shaped, membranous in the basal portion, and projected ventrally; valva spatula-shaped, costa slightly concave, rounded apex and ventral margin straight, editum small with thin and long setae, sacculus rectangular and narrow; fultura inferior U-shaped, with rounded ends and short setae; fultura superior sclerotized, with two arms converging posteriorly, forming an inverted V-shape with numerous spines; aedeagus cylindrical and curved in lateral view and, in dorsal view, bilobed distally, with proximal opening for the ejaculatory ductus rounded and vesica with small cornuti.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1085,2011]" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">
Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[404,488,1877,1903]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–12" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1547,1571]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1524]" captionTargetId="figure-22@11.[151,1435,181,1524]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 9–12. Female genitalia of Hepialodes, Iza, Loxiorhiza and Meskea species in lateral view. 9. H. follicula from Brazil, Goiás, Campinaçu (Barra Mansa farm) (DZ 39.216). 10. I. nubecula from Brazil, S„o Paulo, Salesópolis (Boraceia) (DZ 39.288). 11. L. cervinalis from Bolivia, Santa Cruz, Buenavista (NHMUK 010921618). 12. M. dyspteraria from El Salvador, San Salvador (MSFR). Scale bar 1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4475227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4475227/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
): tergum VIII rectangular in lateral view, lamella antevaginalis slightly sclerotized, ostium membranous; posterior apophyses longer than the anterior apophyses; bursa copulatrix with the beginning of the ductus bursae sclerotized and the corpus bursae four times smaller than the ductus, signum (
<figureCitation box="[1227,1308,1949,1975]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–14" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1618,1642]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1595]" captionTargetId="figure-208@12.[151,1436,561,1595]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 13–14. Signa of Hepialodes and Loxiorhiza species. 13. H. follicula from Brazil, Goiás, Campinaçu (Barra Mansa farm) (DZ 39.216). Scale bar 1mm. 14. L. cervinalis from Bolivia, Santa Cruz, Buenavista (NHMUK 010921618). Scale bar 0,5mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4475229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4475229/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="241">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) oval, with numerous sclerotized spines; papillae anales suboval, as long as tall, covered with thin and short setae.
</paragraph>
